<dl id="n36108h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36108h">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36108h"> 108(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> rest from the danes <small>Black</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36108h"><li>FW 549.07 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36108h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36108h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36108h">MS BL 47484b-84b-380</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:147 <a name="rBd13" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd13">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd13.htm#n36108h">Draft: III&sect;3B.13</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">For forty years, from 875 to 915n the historian&apos;s record &ldquo;<mark>rest from the Danes</mark>&rdquo;, meaning that their wild and continuous raids over the land ceased for a space, and they were compelled to act on the defensive. The explanation is, no doubt, that scenting war and plunder from afar, all the &ldquo;stormy petrels&rdquo; of the nation were away in England fighting Alfred the Great. <small> D.A. Chart, <a name="DACD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#DACD"><cite title="source">The Story of Dublin</cite></a> (1907) 6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
